<HEAD>Stuffed Animals Recalled Because of Choking Hazard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd item, on Indian museum, to change New Mexican to New
Mexico in lead and fix typo in Cheyenne-Arapaho in 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California company is recalling six models
of stuffed animals imported from China because their eyes can
detach, posing a potentially fatal choking hazard.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said Monday there have
been no known deaths or injuries caused by the toys, all of which
contain music boxes.
   The CSPC said the toys have wind-up keys protruding from their
backs and a small white tag sewed to the side or bottom that reads:
``The San Francisco Music Box Company, Emeryville, Ca., Reg. No.
PA-2642 (RC) All New Materials Made In China.''
   Approximately 2,866 of the stuffed animals were distributed
nationwide from December 1988 through June 1989, the CSPC said.
   The names of the animals, their model numbers and the song
played by the music box are:
   _White Jointed Bear, 55-0046, ``You Are My Sunshine.''
   _Beige Jointed Bear, 55-0061, ``Don't Let Me Go.''
   _Beige Small Jointed Bear, 55-0038, ``It's A Small World.''
   _Pink Bear, 55-0079, ``A Baby's Lullabye.''
   _Pink Monkey, 55-0095, ``Zip-a-dee-doo-daa.''
   _Beige Articulated Santa Bear, 55-0368.
</TEXT>
