<HEAD>Prison Population Grows 12 Percent in One Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of inmates in state and federal
prisons grew a record 12 percent last year to 703,687 prisoners,
according to a Justice Department study.
   The inmate population increased 76,099 last year from a 1988
prison population of 627,588 held in state and federal facilities,
said the study by the Bureau of Justice Statistics released Sunday.
   The nation's prison population has more than doubled in the last
decade, from 373,866 inmates in 1980 to 703,687 last year, said the
study.
   Only three states _ Kansas, North Dakota and Alaska _ reported
decreases in prison populations last year. The biggest proportional
increase occurred in Rhode Island, where the number of inmates
jumped 30.1 percent, followed by Colorado, with a 26.9 percent
increase.
   South Dakota had the third highest percentage increase _ 25.2
percent _ and Utah ranked fourth with a 21.3 percent jump.
</TEXT>
