<HEAD>New Indian Museum Director Hopes To Change Native American Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Museum of the American Indian
will be a new type of institution that forever alters the image of
native Americans, according to the New Mexico lawyer selected as
the museum's first director.
   ``My highest aspiration for the National Museum of the American
Indian is that it will reanalyze, redirect and, in many cases,
reformulate entirely the concepts and presentations of the past
concerning Indian culture,'' W. Richard West Jr. said Monday.
   West, of Albuquerque, N.M., and a member of the Cheyenne-Arapaho
tribes, becomes the museum's director effective June 1, the
Smithsonian Institution announced at a news conference Monday.
   West outlined his vision for the museum as a multi-cultural
facility that will reach out, without paternalism or condescension,
to native Americans throughout the hemisphere.
   West, 47, a partner and president of the Indian-owned law firm
of Gover, Steton, Williams &amp; West, has no direct experience running
museums. However, a news release from the Smithsonian stressed his
administrative and fund-raising abilities, and noted he was a
founding member of the Smithsonian's Cultural Education Committee.
   West is also the son of American Indian artist Walter Richard
West Sr. and from 1975 to 1980, was coordinator and treasurer of
the Native American Council of Regents of the Institute of American
Indian Arts in Santa Fe, N.M.
</TEXT>
